The chronology described in the above subsection defines a set of populations and subpopulations as well as a set of flows. They can be depicted as shown in Fig. 2. There the home country population is divided in four subpopulations and the different flows among the subpopulations and their classes are shown. As the disease is considered a vector-transmitted one, the vector population (mosquitoes) and its classes are also included.The first subpopulation (leftmost flow in Fig. 2) comprises those individuals living in the disease-free country, which have never travelled to endemic countries but may eventually acquire the infection locally (autochthonous cases). Consistent with classical S-I-R models (Anderson and May 1991), the individuals in that subpopulation can be classified as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
